[
    {
        "content": "<p>Has anyone here thought about punctual Hilbert schemes?</p>",
        "id": 241717103,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1623024149
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>What's one of those?</p>",
        "id": 241749371,
        "sender_full_name": "Morgan Rogers (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1623057761
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>as in, Hilbert schemes parametrising discrete sets of points?</p>",
        "id": 241769137,
        "sender_full_name": "Tim Hosgood",
        "timestamp": 1623069307
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>if so, then yes, a bit, thinking of them as resolutions of configuration spaces</p>",
        "id": 241769204,
        "sender_full_name": "Tim Hosgood",
        "timestamp": 1623069343
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yes, Hilbert schemes describing sets of points and how they collide: the nth punctual Hilbert scheme of a commutative algebra A, for example, has as its closed points all the ideals J of A such that dim(A/J) = n.</p>",
        "id": 241799600,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1623081822
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Do you know anything about how punctual Hilbert schemes are related to configuration spaces, <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"280178\">@Tim Hosgood</span>?  That's actually one of the things I'm wondering about.  The configuration space whose points are n-tuples of distinct points in an affine variety X seems to inject into the nth punctual Hilbert scheme of the corresponding algebra.</p>",
        "id": 241800084,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1623082035
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>When I hear \"<a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Configuration_space_(mathematics)#Definition\">configuration space</a>\" I think of a space whose points are (ordered or unordered) n-tuples of points in some space X.</p>",
        "id": 241800379,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1623082174
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>If I want to let the points \"collide\" I think of the <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chow_variety#Dimension_0:_Points\">Chow variety</a> of X formed by taking <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>X</mi><mi>n</mi></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X^n</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.664392em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">n</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> and modding out by the action of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>S</mi><mi>n</mi></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">S_n</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.83333em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">S</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.151392em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.5500000000000003em;margin-left:-0.05764em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">n</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>.</p>",
        "id": 241800706,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1623082282
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>There's a map from the punctual Hilbert scheme to the Chow variety, I've heard, and that makes plenty of sense.</p>",
        "id": 241801152,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1623082385
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>yes, the Hilbert scheme <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Hilb</mi><mo>⁡</mo></mrow><mi>n</mi></msup><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>X</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\operatorname{Hilb}^n(X)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mop\"><span class=\"mop\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">Hilb</span></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.748732em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.1473400000000002em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">n</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> comes with a map (called the Hilbert–Chow morphism) into the Chow space <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi>X</mi><mi>n</mi></msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">/</mi><msub><mi>S</mi><mi>n</mi></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X^n/S_n</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.664392em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">n</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mord\">/</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">S</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.151392em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.5500000000000003em;margin-left:-0.05764em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">n</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>, and the Hilbert scheme is nice (i.e. an irreducible smooth variety), and can thus be thought of as a resolution of the Chow space</p>",
        "id": 241804481,
        "sender_full_name": "Tim Hosgood",
        "timestamp": 1623083885
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>if you take a nice example like the affine plane <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi><mo>=</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">A</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X=\\mathbb{A}^2</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8141079999999999em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbb\">A</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8141079999999999em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">2</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>, then you can understand the Hilbert–Chow morphism pretty concretely: the Hilbert scheme is covered by open affines <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>U</mi><mi>λ</mi></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">U_\\lambda</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.83333em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">U</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.33610799999999996em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.5500000000000003em;margin-left:-0.10903em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">λ</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> consisting of ideals of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>I</mi><mo>◃</mo><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">C</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo><mi>x</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>y</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">I\\triangleleft\\mathbb{C}[x,y]</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">I</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">◃</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222222222222222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">C</span><span class=\"mopen\">[</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.16666666666666666em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">y</span><span class=\"mclose\">]</span></span></span></span> such that <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">C</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo><mi>x</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>y</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">/</mi><mi>I</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{C}[x,y]/I</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">C</span><span class=\"mopen\">[</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.16666666666666666em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">y</span><span class=\"mclose\">]</span><span class=\"mord\">/</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">I</span></span></span></span> has a certain basis, where <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>λ</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\lambda</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.69444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">λ</span></span></span></span> corresponds to a partition of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">{</mo><mn>1</mn><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mo>…</mo><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>n</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">}</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\{1,\\ldots,n\\}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">{</span><span class=\"mord\">1</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.16666666666666666em;\"></span><span class=\"minner\">…</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.16666666666666666em;\"></span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.16666666666666666em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">n</span><span class=\"mclose\">}</span></span></span></span> (and this is where Young diagrams come in), and the Hilbert–Chow morphism is then given by sending an ideal <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>I</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">I</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">I</span></span></span></span> to its support <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Supp</mi><mo>⁡</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>I</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>:</mo><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">C</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo><mi>x</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>y</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">/</mi><mi>I</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\operatorname{Supp}(I):=\\mathbb{C}[x,y]/I</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mop\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">Supp</span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">I</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">C</span><span class=\"mopen\">[</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.16666666666666666em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">y</span><span class=\"mclose\">]</span><span class=\"mord\">/</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">I</span></span></span></span> (i.e. the subset of points where all polynomials in the ideal vanish)</p>",
        "id": 241804982,
        "sender_full_name": "Tim Hosgood",
        "timestamp": 1623084106
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>generally what people refer to as the <em>punctual</em> Hilbert scheme (at least when <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> is an affine space) is the smaller thing that consists of ideals <em>supported at the origin</em>, since this tells you about what you mentioned: how points \"collide\"</p>",
        "id": 241805495,
        "sender_full_name": "Tim Hosgood",
        "timestamp": 1623084314
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><a href=\"http://people.math.harvard.edu/~bejleri/Hilbertschemes_gss.pdf\">http://people.math.harvard.edu/~bejleri/Hilbertschemes_gss.pdf</a> is a really nice introduction to this stuff</p>",
        "id": 241805670,
        "sender_full_name": "Tim Hosgood",
        "timestamp": 1623084377
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Thanks!  I found <a href=\"https://www-fourier.ujf-grenoble.fr/sites/ifmaquette.ujf-grenoble.fr/files/bertin_rev.pdf\">Bertin's introduction</a> to punctual Hilbert schemes to be incredibly bureaucratic and unenlightening - it reads more like an introduction to the foundations of algebraic geometry (all the stuff I've never really wanted to learn).</p>",
        "id": 241823646,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1623092212
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>This looks better.</p>",
        "id": 241823659,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1623092221
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I just found out that for varieties of dimension 3 or more, there are points in the punctual Hilbert scheme that aren't \"limits of colliding points\".  <span aria-label=\"scared\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f628\" role=\"img\" title=\"scared\">:scared:</span></p>",
        "id": 241823826,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1623092295
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><a href=\"https://twitter.com/gro_tsen/status/1401961668687564800\">https://twitter.com/gro_tsen/status/1401961668687564800</a></p>\n<div class=\"inline-preview-twitter\"><div class=\"twitter-tweet\"><a href=\"https://twitter.com/gro_tsen/status/1401961668687564800\"><img class=\"twitter-avatar\" src=\"https://uploads.zulipusercontent.net/409aeecc1293a76271e9885fddff3f7f9d061241/68747470733a2f2f7062732e7477696d672e636f6d2f70726f66696c655f696d616765732f313031383231363136373330363132313231372f766e6a41796a79615f6e6f726d616c2e6a7067\"></a><p><a href=\"https://twitter.com/johncarlosbaez\">@johncarlosbaez</a> Actually, if X is <span aria-label=\"eight spoked asterisk\" class=\"emoji emoji-2733\" role=\"img\" title=\"eight spoked asterisk\">:eight_spoked_asterisk:</span>︎any<span aria-label=\"eight spoked asterisk\" class=\"emoji emoji-2733\" role=\"img\" title=\"eight spoked asterisk\">:eight_spoked_asterisk:</span>︎ smooth projective variety of dimension ≥3, then for n≫0, the Hilbert scheme of 0-dimensional subschemes of length n of X is reducible (so it has other components than the “obvious” one consisting of specializations of n distinct points).</p><span>- Gro-Tsen (@gro_tsen)</span></div></div>",
        "id": 241823910,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1623092336
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><a href=\"https://twitter.com/gro_tsen/status/1401962021294329857\">https://twitter.com/gro_tsen/status/1401962021294329857</a></p>\n<div class=\"inline-preview-twitter\"><div class=\"twitter-tweet\"><a href=\"https://twitter.com/gro_tsen/status/1401962021294329857\"><img class=\"twitter-avatar\" src=\"https://uploads.zulipusercontent.net/409aeecc1293a76271e9885fddff3f7f9d061241/68747470733a2f2f7062732e7477696d672e636f6d2f70726f66696c655f696d616765732f313031383231363136373330363132313231372f766e6a41796a79615f6e6f726d616c2e6a7067\"></a><p><a href=\"https://twitter.com/johncarlosbaez\">@johncarlosbaez</a> Ref.: Iarrobino, “Reducibility of the families of 0-dimensional schemes on a variety”, ‘Inv. Math.’, 15 (1972), 72–77. <a href=\"https://t.co/QSi9fJuTVs\">https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/BF01418644</a></p><span>- Gro-Tsen (@gro_tsen)</span></div></div>",
        "id": 241823935,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1623092347
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>oh, that's an unnerving result indeed!</p>",
        "id": 241825142,
        "sender_full_name": "Tim Hosgood",
        "timestamp": 1623092831
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>what's really weird though is if you look at the (weak) bounds given in the paper: it proves that, in three dimensions, <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi></mrow><mi>n</mi></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathrm{Hilb}^n</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.748732em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">Hilb</span></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.748732em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.1473400000000002em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">n</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> is reducible for <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>&gt;</mo><mn>102</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">n&gt;102</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.5782em;vertical-align:-0.0391em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">n</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">&gt;</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.64444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">102</span></span></span></span>, which is quite a lot of points!</p>",
        "id": 241825501,
        "sender_full_name": "Tim Hosgood",
        "timestamp": 1623092965
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>but I also have absolutely zero intuition for why 103 points should suddenly be somehow worse than 102</p>",
        "id": 241825601,
        "sender_full_name": "Tim Hosgood",
        "timestamp": 1623092996
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>although maybe the bounds are much lower for e.g. the affine plane</p>",
        "id": 241825667,
        "sender_full_name": "Tim Hosgood",
        "timestamp": 1623093010
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>but for the affine plane, the Hilbert scheme is always irreducible, thankfully (<a href=\"https://mathoverflow.net/a/20707/73622\">https://mathoverflow.net/a/20707/73622</a>)</p>",
        "id": 241826466,
        "sender_full_name": "Tim Hosgood",
        "timestamp": 1623093370
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Does that paper prove that in 3 dimensions <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi></mrow><mi>n</mi></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathrm{Hilb}^n</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.748732em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">Hilb</span></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.748732em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.1473400000000002em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">n</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> is reducible for n = 102?  </p>\n<p>I doubt it.   I doubt that bound is sharp.</p>",
        "id": 241873075,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1623131053
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Hmm, actually that MathOverflow article you cited points to <a href=\"https://mathoverflow.net/a/20290/2893\">another paper</a> written 46 years later that <em>seems</em> to show that in 4 dimensions <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi></mrow><mi>n</mi></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathrm{Hilb}^n</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.748732em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">Hilb</span></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.748732em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.1473400000000002em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">n</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> is reducible for <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>≥</mo><mn>8</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">n \\ge 8</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7719400000000001em;vertical-align:-0.13597em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">n</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">≥</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.64444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">8</span></span></span></span>.   And this paper seems to give a constructive proof, rather than a dimension-counting argument.</p>",
        "id": 241873573,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1623131676
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>oh, i’d really like to understand a constructive proof, too see what these other components look like. i’ll give it a read</p>",
        "id": 241903375,
        "sender_full_name": "Tim Hosgood",
        "timestamp": 1623152022
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>If you make any progress, even a tiny bit, please let me know.  I sort of bounced off this paper.</p>",
        "id": 241939516,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1623166645
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><a href=\"/user_uploads/21317/sfmDdNu1Rgwl4Nxx4Qa1kBum/Screenshot-2021-06-09-at-00.39.22.png\">Screenshot-2021-06-09-at-00.39.22.png</a> <a href=\"/user_uploads/21317/Qroh5L6HS_KmZQCb6VhWAbU_/Screenshot-2021-06-09-at-00.39.15.png\">Screenshot-2021-06-09-at-00.39.15.png</a> <a href=\"/user_uploads/21317/Ub4f47UImxaFrwdbm4KH9qZw/Screenshot-2021-06-09-at-00.39.00.png\">Screenshot-2021-06-09-at-00.39.00.png</a></p>\n<div class=\"message_inline_image\"><a href=\"/user_uploads/21317/sfmDdNu1Rgwl4Nxx4Qa1kBum/Screenshot-2021-06-09-at-00.39.22.png\" title=\"Screenshot-2021-06-09-at-00.39.22.png\"><img src=\"/user_uploads/21317/sfmDdNu1Rgwl4Nxx4Qa1kBum/Screenshot-2021-06-09-at-00.39.22.png\"></a></div><div class=\"message_inline_image\"><a href=\"/user_uploads/21317/Qroh5L6HS_KmZQCb6VhWAbU_/Screenshot-2021-06-09-at-00.39.15.png\" title=\"Screenshot-2021-06-09-at-00.39.15.png\"><img src=\"/user_uploads/21317/Qroh5L6HS_KmZQCb6VhWAbU_/Screenshot-2021-06-09-at-00.39.15.png\"></a></div><div class=\"message_inline_image\"><a href=\"/user_uploads/21317/Ub4f47UImxaFrwdbm4KH9qZw/Screenshot-2021-06-09-at-00.39.00.png\" title=\"Screenshot-2021-06-09-at-00.39.00.png\"><img src=\"/user_uploads/21317/Ub4f47UImxaFrwdbm4KH9qZw/Screenshot-2021-06-09-at-00.39.00.png\"></a></div>",
        "id": 242001373,
        "sender_full_name": "Tim Hosgood",
        "timestamp": 1623195618
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>looking at these pictures, it doesn't surprise me that you're interested in these things! very intriguing indeed</p>",
        "id": 242001401,
        "sender_full_name": "Tim Hosgood",
        "timestamp": 1623195659
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Where did you see those pictures?</p>\n<p>My <em>real</em> reason for being interested in these things is trying to get a clear visual understanding the geometric McKay correspondence, which gives a way to get the E8 Dynkin diagram out of the double cover of the symmetry group of the icosahedron:</p>\n<p><a href=\"https://johncarlosbaez.wordpress.com/2017/07/02/the-geometric-mckay-correspondence-part-2/\">https://johncarlosbaez.wordpress.com/2017/07/02/the-geometric-mckay-correspondence-part-2/</a></p>",
        "id": 242003185,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1623197267
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>But this correspondence proceeds via an \"equivariant Hilbert scheme of points\", so I need to understand that better.</p>",
        "id": 242003239,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1623197307
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"275920\">John Baez</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229199-learning.3A-questions/topic/punctual.20Hilbert.20schemes/near/242003185\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Where did you see those pictures?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p><a href=\"https://eudml.org/doc/142485\">https://eudml.org/doc/142485</a></p>",
        "id": 242004813,
        "sender_full_name": "Tim Hosgood",
        "timestamp": 1623198753
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>My browser will not let me go to that site - it thinks it's dangerous.</p>",
        "id": 242013584,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1623208531
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Forbidden knowledge.</p>",
        "id": 242027288,
        "sender_full_name": "Nathanael Arkor",
        "timestamp": 1623224579
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Briancon, Joel. \"Description de <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi></mrow><mi>n</mi></msup><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">C</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">{</mo><mi>x</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>y</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">}</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathrm{Hilb}^n\\mathbf{C}\\{x,y\\}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathrm\">Hilb</span></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.748732em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.1473400000000002em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">n</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mord mathbf\">C</span><span class=\"mopen\">{</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">x</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.16666666666666666em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.03588em;\">y</span><span class=\"mclose\">}</span></span></span></span>\" <em>Inventiones mathematicae</em> <strong>41</strong> (1977), 45–90.</p>",
        "id": 242090616,
        "sender_full_name": "Tim Hosgood",
        "timestamp": 1623255084
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"275920\">John Baez</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229199-learning.3A-questions/topic/punctual.20Hilbert.20schemes/near/241939516\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>If you make any progress, even a tiny bit, please let me know.  I sort of bounced off this paper.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>so it seems like the bit that is of interest to you is section 5, where they explicitly construct a point <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>J</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">J</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.09618em;\">J</span></span></span></span> in the non-smoothable component</p>",
        "id": 242090743,
        "sender_full_name": "Tim Hosgood",
        "timestamp": 1623255143
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Thanks, I'll check that out.</p>",
        "id": 242094128,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1623256426
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>i must admit, i'm surprised that i've yet to read an explanation in the form that i think you want (i.e. \"most of the points correspond to particle collisions, except for these exceptional points, which correspond to ???\"</p>",
        "id": 242094370,
        "sender_full_name": "Tim Hosgood",
        "timestamp": 1623256518
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>if this is still a mystery then maybe i'll ask some of my algebraic geometry colleagues</p>",
        "id": 242094420,
        "sender_full_name": "Tim Hosgood",
        "timestamp": 1623256550
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Right, that's the sort of explanation I want.   Maybe nobody knows a simple explanation, which then makes this a nice problem... though not one I'm likely to solve!</p>",
        "id": 242094820,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1623256721
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>So yes, if you know people who are good at this sort of thing, please ask them.</p>",
        "id": 242094894,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1623256764
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><a href=\"/user_uploads/21317/-dhw1qr6jdw181JMlNqZDrMq/Screenshot-2021-06-10-at-13.52.21.png\">Screenshot-2021-06-10-at-13.52.21.png</a> <br>\n(from <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/0812.3342.pdf\">https://arxiv.org/pdf/0812.3342.pdf</a>)</p>\n<div class=\"message_inline_image\"><a href=\"/user_uploads/21317/-dhw1qr6jdw181JMlNqZDrMq/Screenshot-2021-06-10-at-13.52.21.png\" title=\"Screenshot-2021-06-10-at-13.52.21.png\"><img src=\"/user_uploads/21317/-dhw1qr6jdw181JMlNqZDrMq/Screenshot-2021-06-10-at-13.52.21.png\"></a></div>",
        "id": 242200598,
        "sender_full_name": "Tim Hosgood",
        "timestamp": 1623329572
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Nice!</p>",
        "id": 242267920,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1623357749
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I thought this discussion of punctual Hilbert schemes was about Allen Knutson's comments on your Plethysm paper: <a href=\"https://golem.ph.utexas.edu/category/2021/06/schur_functors_and_categorifie.html#c059823\">https://golem.ph.utexas.edu/category/2021/06/schur_functors_and_categorifie.html#c059823</a></p>",
        "id": 242333912,
        "sender_full_name": "Simon Burton",
        "timestamp": 1623412315
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>That's probably why I got back to thinking about punctual Hilbert schemes.  I'd love to understand what he's talking about.   But my real goal here is to finish up my project of understanding the <a href=\"https://johncarlosbaez.wordpress.com/2017/07/02/the-geometric-mckay-correspondence-part-2/\">geometric McKay correspondence</a> in simple terms.</p>\n<p>The crowning glory of this story should go like this:  The 120-cell is a 4-dimensional regular polytope with 120 faces, each shaped like a regular dodecahedron.</p>\n<p>The space <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> of all ways of putting a 120-cell in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">C</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{C}^2</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8141079999999999em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbb\">C</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8141079999999999em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">2</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>, centered at the origin, of any radius including zero, is a singular 2-dimensional complex variety.  It has a singularity corresponding to the 120-cell of radius zero.   We can resolve this singularity and get a smooth complex variety <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mover accent=\"true\"><mi>X</mi><mo>^</mo></mover></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\hat{X}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.9467699999999999em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord accent\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.9467699999999999em;\"><span style=\"top:-3em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span><span style=\"top:-3.25233em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"accent-body\" style=\"left:-0.16666em;\"><span class=\"mord\">^</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>.  The map <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mover accent=\"true\"><mi>X</mi><mo>^</mo></mover><mo>→</mo><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\hat{X} \\to X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.9467699999999999em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord accent\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.9467699999999999em;\"><span style=\"top:-3em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span><span style=\"top:-3.25233em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"accent-body\" style=\"left:-0.16666em;\"><span class=\"mord\">^</span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> is 1-1 except that a bunch of points map to the 120-cell of radius zero.  These points lie in 8 spheres, which intersect each other in this pattern:</p>\n<p><a href=\"/user_uploads/21317/Ex4-O0eWiaLjYG1qbXUQxFvU/e8_dynkin.png\">E8 Dynkin diagram</a></p>\n<div class=\"message_inline_image\"><a href=\"/user_uploads/21317/Ex4-O0eWiaLjYG1qbXUQxFvU/e8_dynkin.png\" title=\"E8 Dynkin diagram\"><img src=\"/user_uploads/21317/Ex4-O0eWiaLjYG1qbXUQxFvU/e8_dynkin.png\"></a></div>",
        "id": 242419943,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1623461340
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>This is amazing, and I've never seen a simple explanation.</p>",
        "id": 242420030,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1623461467
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>where can i read a non-simple explanation?</p>",
